<font color="#FF0000">WANNABEES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov  6 13:50:28 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It's ironic. In the late '60s and early'70s no one wanted to become a Vietnam Vet--especially those who HAD to go, like me.  Now, it seems like every middle-aged man who didn't wants the credit. Is it because they realize that no matter what Vietnam was for those who served and what it did or didn't to them, it was an experience that defined the character of those served? The boys who went came back with a perspective and awareness of their worth and character few others can gain, even in a lifetime of living. As time goes on and it becomes more apparent what a personal sacrifice it really was to serve, you'll be seeing more and more Wannabees sporting war stories, berets, and medals. Don't be afraid to challenge anyone you think is a phony!
<p><code>-- rhoude@mail.moundspk.stpaul.k12.mn.us  (Richard Houde (Vietnam 1969)) </code><p>


